\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Here are several profound focuses and theological opinions drawn from John Piper\'92s writings to help you build an amazing, deep-dive first lesson on the Greatest Commandment (Loving God), while perfectly setting up your second lesson on loving your neighbor.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 Focus 1: Loving God is an Affection, Not Just a Decision or Duty\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 A common misconception is that love is merely an act of the will or an outward deed, because "you cannot command emotions." Piper strongly disagrees: 
\f0\b Jesus 
\f3\i \strokec2 does
\f0\i0 \strokec2  command the emotions
\f1\b0 .\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Loving God is most essentially 
\f3\i treasuring
\f0\i0  God:
\f1\b0  It is an experience of the affections\'97cherishing, delighting in, admiring, and valuing Him above all else.\
\ls6\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 It is not a mere decision:
\f1\b0  You cannot just "decide" to love God any more than you can just decide to love a certain type of music. Something inside you must change so that God becomes 
\f0\b "compellingly beautiful"
\f1\b0  to you. Love for God is a strong inward emotion, not a mere outward action.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Focus 2: The Meaning of Heart, Soul, Mind, and Strength\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Jesus demands that every faculty and capacity of our being express the fullness of our affection for God. While they overlap, they have distinct focuses:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Heart:
\f1\b0  The center of our volitional and emotional life.\
\ls7\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Soul:
\f1\b0  Our human life and personhood as a whole.\
\ls7\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Mind:
\f1\b0  Our thinking capacity.\
\ls7\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Strength:
\f1\b0  The capacity to make vigorous efforts, both bodily and mentally. When Jesus says to love God with 
\f0\b "all"
\f1\b0  of these, He means that there is no part of us that should be uninvolved. Extensively (with every faculty) and intensively (to the highest degree), we are to treasure God.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Focus 3: The Mind Feeds the Heart (Knowing Precedes Loving)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 You cannot love God without knowing God. God is not honored by groundless love; if we do not know anything about God, there is nothing in our mind to awaken love.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Mind's Role:
\f1\b0  Loving God with your mind means 
\f0\b your thinking is wholly engaged to awaken and express the heartfelt fullness of treasuring God
\f1\b0 .\
\ls8\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Jesus is the Litmus Test:
\f1\b0  Jesus is the fullest revelation of God. Therefore, the mind must be used to think about Jesus. If we do not use our minds to know the person and work of Jesus, we cannot truly know or love God.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Focus 4: God Must Be the "Joy of All Our Joys"\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 If we are to love God exclusively ("Whom have I in heaven but you?"), how can we also love our families, friends, or hobbies? Piper answers this by looking at Psalm 43:4, where the psalmist calls God "my exceeding joy" (literally, "the gladness of my rejoicing").\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 In all our rejoicing over the good things God has made, God Himself must be the heart of that joy
\f1\b0 .\
\ls9\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Any joy that does not have God as its central gladness is a hollow joy that will burst like a bubble. You can share Augustine\'92s famous prayer with your class: 
\f2\i "He loves thee too little who loves anything together with Thee, which he loves not for thy sake"
\f1\i0 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Focus 5: Contrast Loving God with "Serving" God\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 Jesus distinguishes between loving God and merely doing things for Him. For instance, Jesus says, "No one can serve two masters, for either he will hate the one and love the other..." (Matthew 6:24).\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Serving is rooted in loving:
\f1\b0  Jesus does not equate loving God with serving God; He roots serving God 
\f2\i in
\f1\i0  loving God.\
\ls10\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Beware of Empty Religion:
\f1\b0  External religious actions are not the essence of love. Jesus rebuked the Pharisees by quoting Isaiah: "This people honors me with their lips, but their heart is far from me; in vain do they worship me" (Mark 7:6-7). The outward behaviors only please God when they flow from a heart that freely treasures Him above all things.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 Focus 6: The Perfect Bridge to Lesson 2 (How the 1st Commandment Sustains the 2nd)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 As you prepare to transition into your second lesson ("Love your neighbor as yourself"), you can use this profound insight: 
\f0\b The First Commandment makes the Second Commandment doable.
\f1\b0 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0
\f0\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Threat of the Second Commandment:
\f1\b0  Loving our neighbor 
\f2\i as ourselves
\f1\i0  feels like a threat because we naturally want to pursue our own happiness (self-love). We fear that loving others with that same zeal will require the suicide of our own happiness.\
\ls11\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Solution in the First Commandment:
\f1\b0  The command to love God with all your heart, soul, and mind means taking 
\f2\i all
\f1\i0  of your longings for joy, security, and significance (your self-love) and finding them completely satisfied in God.\
\ls11\ilvl0
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 The Overflow:
\f1\b0  Once your own self-love has discovered its infinite fulfillment in God, it is no longer threatened by the needs of others. 
\f0\b Your self-love (now fulfilled as God-love) overflows and becomes the measure of your neighbor-love
\f1\b0 . You love others by drawing them into the very joy you have already secured in God. All of Scripture and all of redemptive history hang on these two great realities.\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
